<div id="review_2695110463" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2695110463" />
    <a title="Girish" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5924440-girish"><img alt="Girish" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1591866419p2/5924440.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2695110463?book_show_action=true">Feb 08, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Girish" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Girish" href="/user/show/5924440-girish">Girish</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5924440-girish?shelf=booker">booker</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2695110463" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16513797210724080437"><i>&quot;It might have been better, she felt, if there had never been people, if this turning of the world, and the glistening sea, and the morning breeze happened without witnesses, without anyone feeling, or remembering, or dying, or trying to love.&quot;</i><br/><br/>The simplest of stories can sometimes be impactful. No fancy words, no twists, no major secrets and yet an Irish dysfunctional family story. The Blackwater Lightship is an emotional wreck.<br/> <br/>Helen finds out that her gay brother Declan has AIDS and informs he</span>
  <span id="freeText16513797210724080437" style="display:none"><i>"It might have been better, she felt, if there had never been people, if this turning of the world, and the glistening sea, and the morning breeze happened without witnesses, without anyone feeling, or remembering, or dying, or trying to love."</i><br /><br />The simplest of stories can sometimes be impactful. No fancy words, no twists, no major secrets and yet an Irish dysfunctional family story. The Blackwater Lightship is an emotional wreck.<br /> <br />Helen finds out that her gay brother Declan has AIDS and informs her grandmom and her mom Lily whom she had shut out from her world. They come together under granny's old house by the cliff where the siblings spent their childhood while her mother was dealing with their sick father. Declan's friends join them who have been taking care of him before he had the courage to tell his family. <br /><br />The ladies in the story have their qualms with the past and a strained relationship exists between them. In the company of Declan's friends, they slowly etch and brood away their differences and come together. The characters are well defined and the almost non-dramatic distance between the relations is more realistic. Also the homosexual stories of the friends are expressed in a safe monochrome. <br /><br />The book is the plain vanilla icecream of tragedies - simple and yet worth it. This is also the first book I have read with an AIDS patient!<br /><br />Liked it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16513797210724080437" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


