        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3573588321" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16720179448500998572">This novel is about a young man dying of AIDS, spending time with his family and friends.<br/> <br/>Beginning reading it, I was suddenly brought up short realising he was in the same hospital as as a friend of mine. There is the same game of running around trying to find the consultants. And I liked this comment:<br/> <br/>&apos;Also, it seems to me they don&apos;t really need to have him in hospital.. He has to have a line put back in him.. But after that they probably won&apos;t do anything else to him, just monitor him. It&apos;s r</span>
  <span id="freeText16720179448500998572" style="display:none">This novel is about a young man dying of AIDS, spending time with his family and friends.<br /> <br />Beginning reading it, I was suddenly brought up short realising he was in the same hospital as as a friend of mine. There is the same game of running around trying to find the consultants. And I liked this comment:<br /> <br />'Also, it seems to me they don't really need to have him in hospital.. He has to have a line put back in him.. But after that they probably won't do anything else to him, just monitor him. It's really easy to get into hospital, but really hard to convince them to let you out."<br /><br />It all has the ring of actual experience about it.<br /> <br />He goes to stay at his granny's by the sea. This is despite the fact that he hasn’t previously told his family he’s gay, not even his sister, that he has hidden being ill for three years, and that he really wants his mother’s comfort. He is afraid of his mother’s control and will not go to her house – and she is emphatically distant to his two loyal friends – Paul from the European Commission and Larry who is an architect – who turn up to nurse him. But he lies in her lap being comforted as they return after a few days to the Dublin hospital, as a minor virus takes over his body with vomiting and diarrhoea.<br /><br />The story is told entirely from the perspective of his sister, coming to terms with her difficult relationship with mother and grandmother, with her loss of her father to cancer as child. She felt abandoned in her mother’s house as a child, as her mother stayed with her father in Dublin as he was dying, as no one told her anything. She has a life of a successful headmistress, meeting the Minister to discuss her good practice in reducing absenteeism. The return to the crumbling damp house by the sea puts all that to one side as unimportant. And she fears leaving her children alone – even with their father – in case they experience the same sense of abandonment and do not speak.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16720179448500998572" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


